 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Adrien, Andre, Armand, Cecile, Celine, Dany, Gaetan, Herve, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Lucien.","French: habitational name from Rochefort, the name of several places in various parts of France.","English: variant of   Ratchford  . Compare   Rochford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rocheford","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Fernand.","Altered form of French   Rochefort  ."]},{"name":"Ratchford","meanings":["habitational name from Rochford (Worcestershire), from Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’ (genitive <i>ræcces</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","habitational name from Rochford (Essex). Early forms of the name ending in <i>Ro-</i> suggest that the placename derives from Old English <i>hrōc</i> ‘rook’ or the Old English personal name <i>Hrōc(a)</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, but the 13th century forms in <i>Ra-</i> and <i>Re-</i> suggest that the first element is Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’.","English:"]}]},{"name":"Payen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Pagen</i>, <i>Paien</i>, from Latin <i>Paganus</i>, from <i>paganus</i> ‘country-dweller’, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘of or relating to the countryside’, possibly given to a child not yet baptized (because of its later sense of ‘pagan, heathen’). Alternatively, a nickname for a country-born person. This surname is also found in the West Indies (mainly Haiti) and Mauritius.","English: variant of   Payne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Payan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Ramon, Carlos, Jesus, Leticia, Luis, Ana, Cruz, Juana, Roberto, Rodolfo.","Spanish (<b>Payán</b>): perhaps from Mozarab <i>päiên</i> ‘cave, ravine’, from Hispanic Latin <i>pedia</i>, derived from <i>pedem</i> ‘foot’. In Spain, this surname is found mainly in Andalusia.","French: Occitan variant of   Payen  ."]},{"name":"Pesnell","meanings":["Probably an altered form of French (Normandy) <b>Pesnel</b>: from a vernacular pet form of the old personal name   Payen  , or a topographic name for someone who lived by a fence or palissade, from a shortened form of <i>paissenel</i>, <i>pessenel</i>, a diminutive of <i>paisson</i>, <i>pesson</i> ‘post, stake’. This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Pean","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Seán (pronounced ‘shawn’), Irish equivalent of   John .  The name has always been common in Ireland, but since the 1960s has frequently been chosen (usually without the accent) by parents who have no Irish connections. One influence on its popularity has been the actor  Sean Connery  (  b. 1930 ), of  James Bond  fame ."]},{"name":"Payne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Payen de Rochefort was born about 1140, in France, his father, Pierre de Rochefort-sur-Loire Seigneur de Rochefort seigneur de Montjean, was 52 and his mother, Burgondie de Craon, was 52. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Burgonde de Brienne de Beaumont. He died about 1190, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1140–about 1190":"umbes 1140–umbes 1190","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1155–1222":"1155–1222","1165–1222":"1165–1222","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1090":"1090","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1 JAN 1165":"1. jaanuar 1165","1140":"1140","Bressuire,79049,Deux-Sèvres,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Bressuire, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1140–about 1190":"noin 1140–noin 1190","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1140–1190":"1140–1190","1140–F